issidents or conformists to the regime and sees them as navigators and negotiators among diverse political discourses and interests. She questions the fetishization of marginalized communities among practitioners of progressive art and politics, arguing that the members of minjian are often more complex, defiant, and savvy than the elites would assume. The Minjian Avant-Garde critically assesses the rise of populism in both art and politics and show that minjian could constitute either a democratizing or a coercive force.This book was published with generous support from the George Dewey and Mary J. Krumrine Endowment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and social actionzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt and social actionzChinaxHistoryy21st century. 0aArt and societyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt and societyzChinaxHistoryy21st century. 0aArtists and communityzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtists and communityzChinaxHistoryy21st century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zChinaxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial practice (Art)zChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial practice (Art)zChinaxHistoryy21st century. 4aArt History. 4aCULTURAL STUDIES. 7aART / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aart critics, art history, museum curators, artistic vision, sociopolitical studies, Antoni Negri, modern China, minjian avant-garde, Ai Weiwei, anti-Asian racism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150177320440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773204/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-